  'refLinkInstructions' => 
  array (
    'en_US' => '<h4>To Add Reference Linking to the Layout Process</h4><p>When turning a submission into HTML or PDF, make sure that all hyperlinks in the submission are active.</p><h4>A. When the Author Provides a Link with the Reference</h4><ol><li>While the submission is still in its word processing format (e.g., Word), add the phrase VIEW ITEM to the end of the reference that has a URL.</li><li>Turn that phrase into a hyperlink by highlighting it and using Word\'s Insert Hyperlink tool and the URL prepared above.</li></ol><h4>B. Enabling Readers to Search Google Scholar For References</h4><ol><li>While the submission is still in its word processing format (e.g., Word), copy the title of the work referenced in the References list (if it appears to be too common a title—e.g., "Peace"—then copy author and title).</li><li>Paste the reference\'s title between the %22\'s, placing a + between each word: http://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=%22PASTE+TITLE+HERE%22</li><li>Add the phrase GS SEARCH to the end of each citation in the submission\'s References list.</li><li>Turn that phrase into a hyperlink by highlighting it and using Word\'s Insert Hyperlink tool and the URL prepared in #2.</li></ol><h4>C. Enabling Readers to Search for References with a DOI</h4><ol><li>While the submission is still in Word, copy a batch of references into CrossRef Text Query http://www.crossref.org/freeTextQuery/.</li><li>Paste each DOI that the Query provides in the following URL (between = and &amp;): http://www.cmaj.ca/cgi/external_ref?access_num=PASTE DOI#HERE&amp;link_type=DOI.</li><li>Add the phrase CrossRef to the end of each citation in the submission\'s References list.</li><li>Turn that phrase into a hyperlink by highlighting the phrase and using Word\'s Insert Hyperlink tool and the appropriate URL prepared in #2.</li></ol>',
  ),
  'reviewGuidelines' => 
  array (
    'en_US' => 'Abstract<br /><ul><li>Is there an abstract or brief summary of the work?  Is there a concluding section?</li></ul>Length<br /><ul><li>Does it meet the length guidelines?  Should it be shortened and reconsidered in another format?</li></ul><p>Originality</p><ul><li>Is this the right journal for the article? Is the work relevant and novel?  Does it contain significant additional material to that already published?</li></ul><p>Presentation</p><ul><li>Is the writing style clear and appropirate to the readership?  Are tables/graphics clear to read and labeled appropriately?  Has the author received permission to use pictures?</li></ul><p>Relevance</p><ul><li>Does it help to expand or further research in the subject area? </li></ul><p>Significance/Scope</p><ul><li>Does the paper fit the scope of the journal? Is it written by a Post-graduate trainee/Resident/Fellow? </li></ul><p>Recommendations should be one of five:</p><p>1. Accept Submission (suitable for publication in current form)</p><p>2. Revision Required (ready for publication after light revisions--list the revisions you would expect from the author)</p><p>3. Resubmit for Review (if the paper would benefit from substantial changes such as expanded data analysis, widening of the literature review, or rewriting sections)</p><p>4. Resubmit Elsewhere (the paper is not suitable for publication with this journal)</p><p>5. Decline Submission (this paper does not meet required guidelines)</p>',
  ),
  'reviewPolicy' => 
  array (
    'en_US' => '<p dir="ltr" align="left">For authors, the time from receipt of submission to the first decision is four weeks and from acceptance to publication is 12 weeks. OSMP\'s acceptance rate is approximately 25%.</p><p dir="ltr" align="left">Submissions are first reviewed to determine if basic criteria are met.  If basic criteria are not met, the manuscript will be returned to the author.  If all the basic crteria are met, the manuscript will go on to the chief editor who will either reject or accept the manuscript in a double blind review. </p><p dir="ltr" align="left">If the manuscript is accepted, it will go on to two reviewers who have expertise in the area. If the manuscript is accepted by both peer reviewers, it will return to the section editor with recommendations.  If both peer reviewers reject the manuscript, it will be rejected.  If only one peer reviewer accepts the manuscript, it will return to the section editor for final decisions.</p><p dir="ltr" align="left">If the decision is to accept the manuscript, the section editor will  send the manuscript on to the author for revision. Once all recommendations are completed, the author will return the manuscript to the section editor who will either reject the manuscript or accept for publication. Once accepted, an editorial board meeting will occur and an issue will be designated and the manuscript will be published.</p><p style="background: #fbfbf3; margin-bottom: 7.5pt; vertical-align: top;"><span style="background: #fbfbf3; color: #333333; font-family: \'Helvetica\',sans-serif; font-size: 11pt;">For authors, the time from receipt of submission to the first decision is four weeks and from acceptance to publication is 12 weeks. OSMP\'s acceptance rate is approximately 25%.</span></p><p style="background: #fbfbf3; margin-bottom: 7.5pt; vertical-align: top;"><span style="background: #fbfbf3; color: #333333; font-family: \'Helvetica\',sans-serif; font-size: 11pt;">Submissions are first reviewed to determine if basic criteria are met.  If basic criteria are not met, the manuscript will be returned to the author.  If all the basic crteria are met, the manuscript will go on to the section editor who will either reject or accept the manuscript in a double blind review. </span></p><p style="background: #fbfbf3; margin-bottom: 7.5pt; vertical-align: top;"><span style="background: #fbfbf3; color: #333333; font-family: \'Helvetica\',sans-serif; font-size: 11pt;">If the manuscript is accepted, it will go on to two reviewers who have expertise in the area. If the manuscript is accepted by both peer reviewers, it will return to the section editor with recommendations.  If both peer reviewers reject the manuscript, it will be rejected.  If only one peer reviewer accepts the manuscript, it will return to the section editor for final decisions</span></p><p><span style="background: #fbfbf3; color: #333333; font-family: \'Helvetica\',sans-serif; font-size: 11pt;">If the decision is to accept the manuscript, the section editor will send the manuscript on to the author for revision.  Once all recommendations are completed, the author will return the manuscript to the section editor who will either reject the manuscript or accept for publication.  Once accepted, an editorial board meeting will occur and an issue will be designated and the manuscript will be published.</span></p>',
  ),
